Data cleansing and exploratory data analysis¶

In [10]:
# Checking if there are any duplicate records in the dataset and if present then dropping them.

def checkDuplicate(*dataset):
    for df_name, df in dataset:
        duplicate_values = df.duplicated().sum()
        print(f"{duplicate_values} duplicate values in {df_name} dataset")
        if duplicate_values > 0:
            print(f"Duplicate values were present in {df_name} and have been removed.")
            df.drop_duplicates(inplace = True)

checkDuplicate(("Events", events), ("Gender_Age", gender_age), ("Phone_Device", phone_device))

0 duplicate values in Events dataset
0 duplicate values in Gender_Age dataset
523 duplicate values in Phone_Device dataset
Duplicate values were present in Phone_Device and have been removed.

Univariate Analysis¶

In [16]:
# Plotting Histogram for numerical columns

def numHist():
    num_col = [('Age', 'age'), ('Latitude', 'latitude'), ('Longitude', 'longitude')]
    for colName, col in num_col:
        plt.figure(figsize = (12, 6))
        sb.histplot(df[col].dropna(), kde = True, bins = 30)
        plt.title(f'{colName} Distribution')
        plt.xlabel(colName)
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')
        plt.show()

numHist()

OBSERVATION¶

  • Age Distribution: The graph indicates a peak population age between 25 and 35 years old. A notable decline in population is observed after the age of 40.

  • Latitude Distribution: The majority of the geographic data is concentrated between latitudes 20 and 45 degrees. However, there are some potential outliers with latitude values of 0, which may contain errors.

  • Longitude Distribution: The primary geographic focus lies between longitudes 100 and 140 degrees. Similar to latitude, there are instances of 0 longitude values that might be inaccurate.

# Encoding Categorical Variables in the dataset

def objToInt(df_series):
    if df_series.dtype == 'object':
        df_series = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(df_series)
    return df_series

dfCopy = df.copy()
encoded_df = dfCopy.apply(lambda x: objToInt(x))

# Variance Explained and Cummulative Variance Explained

total = sum(eig_vals)
var_exp = [ (i / total) * 100  for i in sorted(eig_vals, reverse = True)]
cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp)
print('Variance Explained: ', var_exp)
print('Cummulative Variance Explained: ', cum_var_exp)

K-Means Clustering¶

# 

cluster_range = range(1, 15)
cluster_error = []
for val in cluster_range:
    clusters = KMeans(n_clusters = val, n_init = 10)
    clusters.fit(pca_data)
    
    labels = clusters.labels_
    centroid = clusters.cluster_centers_
    
    cluster_error.append(clusters.inertia_)

clusters_df = pd.DataFrame({'num_clusters': cluster_range, 'cluster_errors': cluster_error})

# Computing silhouette score for evaluating the quality of the K means clustering technique.

for i in range(2, 15):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i)
    kmeans = kmeans.fit(pca_data)
    labels = kmeans.predict(pca_data)
    silhouette = silhouette_score(pca_data, labels)
    print(i, silhouette)

# Computing silhouette score for evaluating the quality of the Agglomerative clustering technique.

for i in range(2, 15):
    hier = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = i)
    hier = hier.fit(pca_data)
    label = hier.fit_predict(pca_data)
    print(i, silhouette_score(pca_data, label))
